    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>New York 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> decr 1868<lb/>
            Sunday mrg<lb/>
            Revd S. Morais<lb/>
            My dear sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I must crave your pardon<lb/> for now &#38; then trespassing on your<lb/> valuable time to make a Religious<lb/> inquiry but I have no portuguese<sic></sic><lb/> authority here &#38; do not like taking<lb/> &#34;Dew&#34; of the Germans Dayanim here<lb/></p>
            <p>You can see the fuss which has<lb/> been made about the &#34;Kursheedt&#34;<lb/> marriage.  The &#91;crossed&#45;out&#93; of &#34;Times&#34;<lb/> of to day has the article upon it<lb/> &#38; gives the approval of &#91;&#63;&#93; &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> of Jerusalem &#38; &#91;&#63;&#93; Dr. Arbons.<lb/>  &#91;&#63;&#93; the day after the marriage<lb/> was celebrated here lay an <hi rend="underline">obscure</hi><lb/> German Beth Amedrash man.<lb/></p>
            <p>I think it very ill advised to bring<lb/> these matters into Christian papers<lb/> &#38; especially as M. S. is one of the<lb/> family&#44; but enough of this.<lb/></p>
            <p>My question now concerns<lb/> &#34;Tebila&#34;  In this country where<lb/> every house possesses a Bath<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>of running water&#44; I desire to<lb/> know&#44; if this is not all sufficient<lb/> for a Lady to use every month<lb/> instead of going to the public &#34;mikve&#34;<lb/></p>
            <p>The only difference in the two<lb/> as I can see consists in the one<lb/> being made deep in the ground<lb/> to go down with steps.  But no<lb/> other difference.  The water used<lb/> in one House is the same &#38;<lb/> introduced in the same way<lb/> <hi rend="underline">by pipes</hi> as at the &#39;Mikve&#39; Hence<lb/> why should not the Bath at home<lb/> be as much according to Din<lb/> as the public Mikve&#63;  Provided<lb/> it is taken properly viz by entire<lb/> submersion of the whole Body<lb/> head &#38; all.<lb/></p>
            <p>An early reply to this question<lb/> will be esteemed a great favor<lb/> as my wife is very particular<lb/> but as the distance is great<lb/> &#38; the Mikve being badly &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/> &#40;our congregation has <hi rend="underline">none</hi>&#41; Wed like to<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>spare her the extra trouble.<lb/></p>
            <p><hi rend="underline">Another question</hi> is this<lb/> A Lady has sprained her finger<lb/> so she cannot get her wedding<lb/> over the joints without <hi rend="underline">cutting</hi><lb/> it off.  Is the Tebela perfect<lb/> &#38; according to Din if she keeps<lb/> on said Ring.  Provided the<lb/> water can pass between the<lb/> Ring &#38; the flesh with it on<lb/></p>
            <p>We are having very unpleasant<lb/> weather now &#38; I suppose you are<lb/> no better off.  New Year&#39;s day<lb/> &#40;1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> January&#41; seems to be always wet<lb/> &#38; dreary.<lb/></p>
            <p>I trust yr. good Lady &#38; family<lb/> are all well &#38; hearty.  Why do you<lb/> not come on to New York sometime<lb/> &#38; pay us a visit.  We&#39;d be delighted to<lb/> see you here.<lb/></p>
            <p>Wishing you well over the &#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/>
            				yours very Truly<lb/>
            					J. Abicasis&#91;&#63;&#93;<lb/></p>
            <p>address<lb/>
            Box 481. P. O.<lb/>
            New York<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>J. Abicasis Esqre<lb/>
            Phila January &#91;&#63;&#93; 1868<lb/>
            My dear sir<lb/></p>
            <p>I hasten to reply to the questions propounded in<lb/> your favor just received.  An ordinary bath&#45;tub&#44;<lb/> will not&#8212;rabinically&#45;&#45;be considered sufficient for the purpose<lb/> you need&#59; but you might have one expressly made with<lb/> the proper dimension&#44; and according to the rules laid<lb/> down in the Talmud&#44; and embodied in the &#91;Hebrew&#93; par 201.<lb/>  There is&#44; no doubt&#44; in your city some person on whose knowledge<lb/> and honesty you could depend&#44; to superintend the construction thereof&#44;<lb/> Regarding the ring&#44; that cannot be taken off&#44; by reason of an<lb/> accident to the finger&#44; we are explicitly told by the sages&#44; and Mai&#45;<lb/>monides records their words in treatise &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; that when the water<lb/> passes through&#44; the Tebilah <hi rend="underline">is perfect</hi>.<lb/></p>
            <p>Like yourself&#44; I regret what has happened respecting the<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; given by Mr H. and the more deeply because<lb/> it has proved a &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; yet&#44; if the party had only waited&#44;<lb/> till the favorable answer &#40;which I always believed it would be<lb/> received&#41; had come&#44; all the unpleasantness would have been<lb/> avoided.<lb/></p>
            <p>Trusting that your dear ones are all in the enjoyment of<lb/> good health&#44; I remain<lb/>
            Yours respectfully<lb/>
            S. Morais<lb/></p>
            
        </body>
